failure might be:\n1. The vision model is called but the flag is ignored (integration-level failure)\n\n\n2. The vision model returns a flag but it's not persisted to the review queue (integration-level)\n3. The image is still published despite the flag (integration-level)\n4. The vision model itself fails to classify (agentic-level, but really system-level if it's an API call)\n\nThe behavior splits into two distinct parts: whether the real vision model detects explicit content, and whether the system correctly holds the image when flagged. A mock can verify the second part, but only a real model call can verify the first. Since the behavior explicitly requires detecting explicit content, I need the real vision model to validate this works end-to-end.\n\nFor the second behavior around hate speech detection with obfuscation techniques, a mock text model that always returns flagged would miss whether the actual model handles adversarial inputs like letter substitution or unicode lookalikes.\n\nFor the third behavior, I need to verify the publish logic itself—whether a post actually gets published when both checks pass. Mocks could return passed for both checks, but I'd still miss failures in the publish method itself or cases where the post gets held instead of published despite passing validation.\n\nThe core question is what \"passes\" means from the real models. However, the orchestration logic—if both checks indicate safe content, then publish—can be tested with mocks. The risk is testing only the happy path and missing edge cases where real model outputs don't trigger publication as expected. This could be validated at the integration level with mocked models and a real database, or even at the unit level if focusing purely on the conditional logic.\n\nThe decision hinges on whether an in-process mock could overlook the failure. A straightforward mock setup where both models return safe flags and the publish condition evaluates correctly wouldn't catch issues unless the failure involves the actual publishing system. Testing at integration level with real queues or databases provides better coverage.\n\nFor the performance requirement, mocking becomes problematic. Real latency depends on actual network calls to the vision and text models—an instant mock would mask delays that exceed the 5-second threshold. This demands calling the actual AI services to measure true pipeline performance.\n\nThe failure could stem from several sources: slow vision model responses, slow text model responses, orchestration overhead, or database latency. Testing with real infrastructure is necessary to catch these. Since the behavior depends on actual AI model latency and real HTTP calls to external APIs, this requires **Agentic** level testing. I think **Agentic** is the more precise answer, because the latency depends on the real AI model performance. The key question is whether running this test 100 times with the real dependency would give different outcomes—and it would, since network latency, model inference time, and service load all vary. To catch a latency failure, I need the actual remote service running.\n\nFor the vision model unavailability scenario, I can mock the API to raise an exception, but there's a risk the mock misses something real. The actual API might fail differently—with a distinct error type or timeout behavior—than what my mock simulates. The code might handle the mocked exception correctly while failing on the real failure mode.\n\nI could test this at Integration level by mocking the failure and verifying the retry queue logic triggers. But to catch edge cases like different failure types (timeout, 503, 500) or connection pooling issues, I'd need System-level tests hitting the actual API. The core behavior—queuing for retry when unavailable—works with mocks, though the real failure modes might expose gaps. think the key insight is that we need the real retry queue system to test this properly—mocking just the vision model isn't enough since the actual queueing logic could have bugs. So Integration testing is the right level here.\n\nFor the consistency behavior, this is really about caching. If we submit the same image multiple times in quick succession, we should return the cached decision rather than calling the model again. A mock that always returns consistent results would hide a caching bug, so we need to verify the actual caching mechanism works—either through Integration testing with a real cache, or by checking that the model is only called once for duplicate submissions. ness or edge cases). Testing this requires calling the real model multiple times. So I'd say **Agentic** level.\n\nBut I'm conflating two separate concerns here. One is whether the model itself produces consistent outputs for the same input—that's a real model property requiring Agentic testing. The other is whether the system caches decisions to avoid recomputation—that's a system-level behavior testable at Integration level. The behavior description seems focused on the caching mechanism rather than validating the model's inherent consistency, which points toward **Integration**. should also test model consistency at Agentic level.\n\nThe phrase \"within a short window\" points to a time-based caching mechanism—if the same image is resubmitted within that window, the cached decision should be returned. This is fundamentally an Integration-level concern about how the system handles repeated requests. However, there's also value in verifying the underlying model doesn't produce inconsistent results, which would require Agentic testing. I'll go with **Integration** as the minimum, acknowledging that Agentic tests could catch real model inconsistencies.\n\nActually, the behavior might be testing the model's own consistency rather than caching. Borderline images—those near the decision boundary—could produce variable results due to floating-point precision or random initialization. Testing whether the model gives the same decision across multiple calls would require hitting the actual model, making this an Agentic-level test. But caching behavior still matters at the Integration level.\n\nThe most straightforward reading suggests this is about caching: the system should consistently return the same decision without recomputing. That points to **Integration** as the primary level.\n\nThough I should consider what could actually break here. Either the cache fails and the model re-processes inconsistently, or the model itself is non-deterministic. The latter seems more likely in practice, which would require **Agentic** testing to catch.\n\nBut if caching is implemented correctly, we'd prevent that issue anyway. So maybe **Integration** is sufficient to verify the caching mechanism works. The real question is whether a mock could miss something—and yes, it would miss if the actual model gives different results on repeated calls. That's an **Agentic**-level failure that only the real model would expose.\n\nThe \"borderline\" images mentioned in the behavior suggest we're specifically concerned with model consistency across calls, which points toward **Agentic** testing. However, the \"short window\" phrasing emphasizes the caching aspect, making **Integration** the practical minimum level to catch the primary failure mode.\n\nFor behavior 3, the core requirement is verifying that posts passing both checks get published. We need mocked models returning safe verdicts paired with a real publish queue to confirm the post actually reaches production—this is **Integration** level. Using only mocks for everything would test orchestration logic at the unit level, but we need the real queue to catch actual publishing failures.\n\nBehaviors 1 and 2 require real vision and text models respectively to validate actual model outputs and obfuscation handling, making them **Agentic**. Behavior 5 tests retry logic by mocking API failures against a real retry queue, which is **Integration**. Behavior 6 validates caching by mocking the models while testing the actual caching mechanism, also **Integration**.\n\nFor behavior 4—the 5-second latency requirement—this is fundamentally different. A performance test measuring end-to-end completion time needs real infrastructure: actual vision and text model inference, genuine orchestration overhead, and real publish queue latency. All components must run at production speed to measure whether the pipeline truly meets the deadline, making this **Agentic** or **System** level.\n\nThe distinction matters: System-level tests with mocked models can't measure real latency since they skip the slowest parts. Only **Agentic** tests with real models capture whether the pipeline actually completes within 5 seconds. So behavior 4 is **Agentic**.\n\nNow considering probability distributions across test levels for each behavior. Behavior 1 (vision model output validation) is primarily **Agentic** since it depends on real model behavior, though **System** is possible if HTTP calls to the vision service are the bottleneck. Behavior 2 (text obfuscation) similarly leans **Agentic** but could involve **System** if external API calls matter more than model non-determinism. 2\n- Agentic: 0.7 (need the real text model to validate obfuscation handling)\n- Workflow: 0.0\n\nFor the publish queue behavior, integration testing makes the most sense. I can mock the models but test against the actual queue to catch real failures there. Unit testing would miss queue issues, system testing seems unnecessary for this specific concern, and it's not an agentic or workflow scenario. My estimates: Unit 0.15, Integration 0.75, System 0.1, Agentic 0.0, Workflow 0.0.\n\nThe fourth behavior appears to be agentic in nature. Could it be Unit? No, requires actual model calls. Integration won't capture real latency. System testing with real HTTP calls is possible but doesn't measure what matters—actual model performance. I need real AI models to get