he same borderline image twice within 5 seconds and confirm both get the same outcome, checking whether caching is involved if implemented.\n\nI should verify my test cases align with the original requirements. The issue specifies that explicit images should be flagged and held, hate speech should be caught regardless of obfuscation, safe posts should publish immediately, and the pipeline should complete within a defined latency threshold.\n\nFor the minimum_level assignments, I need to ensure they match what each test actually exercises. Behaviors 1, 2, and 4 use real models so they're Agentic-level. Behaviors 3, 5, and 6 mock components or test specific logic paths, making them Integration-level tests.\n\nNow checking the probability distributions. Each behavior's level_probabilities needs to sum to 1.0 and reflect how likely the test is to run at each level. Behaviors 1 and 2 heavily favor Agentic (0.6 and 0.7) since they depend on real model availability. Behavior 3 is almost entirely Integration (0.75) with some Unit coverage. Behavior 4 splits between System and Agentic. I need to verify Behavior 5's probabilities sum correctly and continue through Behavior 6. ration logic, not model accuracy.\n\nBehavior 4 Justification:\nThe failure mode here is the system not properly handling concurrent requests—race conditions or state corruption when multiple posts are processed simultaneously. We need real concurrency infrastructure to expose timing-dependent bugs, but the models can be mocked since we're testing orchestration under load, not model behavior.\n\nBehavior 5 Justification:\nVerifying that rejected posts are correctly logged requires real persistence and audit infrastructure. The models can be mocked since the failure we're catching is improper logging or missing audit trails, not model accuracy.\n\nBehavior 6 Justification:\nThis tests the system's ability to gracefully degrade when the vision model fails. We need the real vision model to actually fail (or